Research Question #2: Coping Strategies
In an era of extreme competitiveness involving severe academic anxiety due to high
parental expectations, excessive homework, societal demands, social disapproval, and peer
pressure (Mathew et al., 2015, as cited in J. Jain & M. Jain, 2007), students need a social support
system to overcome this academic stress. Social support may include emotional and financial aid
from family, teachers, social media, and friends in times of stress (Bhargava & Tiwari, 2019).
Coping strategies are responses to psychological stress in an effort to maintain mental health and
emotional well-being ("UCLA Dual Diagnosis," n.d.). There are two broad categories of coping
strategies: active and avoidant.
Active coping strategies focus on reducing stress by detecting and tackling the stressors
("UCLA Dual Diagnosis," n.d.). The research study conducted by Mathew et al. (2015) asserts
that students in India most frequently practice active coping methods such as positive reframing,
planning, and instrumental support from parents, teachers, and peers. Parikh et al. (2019) claim
that students are most likely to seek advice and instrumental support from parents and teachers
during academic difficulties, and to receive emotional support from peers during times when
adults cease to be "open-minded" (e.g., romantic relationships, sexual harassment, etc.).
However, in contrast to the results by Mathew et al. (2015), Parikh et al. (2019) claim that active
problem-solving is relatively uncommon overall and primarily confined to older adolescents.
